hands_on_practices.solution:
1. The definitions for the components of the stress-energy tensor $T^{\mu\nu}$ in SI units are:
$$u_{em}=\tfrac{1}{2}\epsilon_0|\mathbf E|^2+\tfrac{1}{2\mu_0}|\mathbf B|^2,\quad 
\mathbf S=\tfrac{1}{\mu_0}(\mathbf E\times\mathbf B),$$
$$\sigma^{ij}
=\epsilon_0\bigl(E^iE^j-\tfrac{1}{2}\delta^{ij}|\mathbf E|^2\bigr)
+\tfrac{1}{\mu_0}\bigl(B^iB^j-\tfrac{1}{2}\delta^{ij}|\mathbf B|^2\bigr),$$
$$T^{00}=u_{em},\;
T^{0i}=T^{i0}=S^i/c,\;
T^{ij}=-\sigma^{ij},\;
T^\mu_{\ \nu}=T^{\mu\alpha}\eta_{\alpha\nu}.$$

2. We can align the coordinate system with the fields without loss of generality. Since $\mathbf E \parallel \mathbf B$, let's set $\mathbf E=(E,0,0)$ and $\mathbf B=(B,0,0)$.
With this alignment, the Poynting vector is $\mathbf S = \frac{1}{\mu_0}(\mathbf E \times \mathbf B) = 0$.
The Maxwell stress tensor components are:
$$
\sigma^{11}=\epsilon_0\bigl(E^2-\tfrac{1}{2}E^2\bigr) + \tfrac{1}{\mu_0}\bigl(B^2-\tfrac{1}{2}B^2\bigr) = \tfrac{1}{2}\epsilon_0E^2+\tfrac{1}{2\mu_0}B^2=u_{em}
$$
$$
\sigma^{22}=\epsilon_0\bigl(0-\tfrac{1}{2}E^2\bigr) + \tfrac{1}{\mu_0}\bigl(0-\tfrac{1}{2}B^2\bigr) = -u_{em}
$$
$$
\sigma^{33} = \sigma^{22} = -u_{em}
$$
All off-diagonal components $\sigma^{ij}$ for $i \neq j$ are zero.

3. Now we construct the contravariant tensor $T^{\mu\nu}$:
$$
T^{\mu\nu} = \begin{pmatrix}
T^{00} & T^{01} & T^{02} & T^{03} \\
T^{10} & T^{11} & T^{12} & T^{13} \\
T^{20} & T^{21} & T^{22} & T^{23} \\
T^{30} & T^{31} & T^{32} & T^{33}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
u_{em} & 0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -\sigma^{11} & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -\sigma^{22} & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 0 & -\sigma^{33}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
u_{em} & 0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -u_{em} & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & u_{em} & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 0 & u_{em}
\end{pmatrix}
$$

4. We find the mixed tensor $T^\mu_{\ \nu}$ by lowering one index with $\eta_{\alpha\nu}=\mathrm{diag}(1, -1, -1, -1)$:
$$T^\mu_{\ \nu} = T^{\mu\alpha}\eta_{\alpha\nu} = \mathrm{diag}(T^{00}\eta_{00}, T^{11}\eta_{11}, T^{22}\eta_{22}, T^{33}\eta_{33})$$
$$T^\mu_{\ \nu} = \mathrm{diag}(u_{em}(1),\ (-u_{em})(-1),\ u_{em}(-1),\ u_{em}(-1)) = \mathrm{diag}(u_{em},\,u_{em},\,-u_{em},\,-u_{em})$$

5. The eigenvalues of a diagonal matrix are its diagonal elements. The eigenvalues are therefore $\{u_{em},\,u_{em},\,-u_{em},\,-u_{em}\}$. The unique positive eigenvalue is $u_{em}$.
$$\lambda_+ = u_{em}=\tfrac{1}{2}\epsilon_0E^2+\tfrac{1}{2\mu_0}B^2.$$
